The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, August 19, 2004 				 Dax eyes Rs 100cr turnover in three years
 ALOKANANDA GHOSH																								Calcutta, Aug. 18: The Chennai-based Dax Networks has set a target of Rs 100-crore turnover by March 2007.																								Country manager C. Sujit Singh said, The company will adopt a strategy to penetrate the domestic core networking market, which is currently growing at 30 per cent. While Dax will continue to provide solutions in all networking technologies, there will be an increased focus on mature and high-value networking technologies such as switching, cabling and routing.																								The company expects to grab a 10 per cent share of the core networking market, which is currently estimated at Rs 1,500 crore.																								Dax achieved a turnover of Rs 62 crore in 2003-04. It expects to grow to Rs 85 crore by March 2006, of which 74 per cent revenue will come from core businesses.																								The company sources its products from contract manufacturers in China, Israel and Taiwan and markets them in India under the Dax brand.																								Singh said the company would also focus on marketing its products and spend 1.5 per cent of its revenues to enhance the brand value in India. A 3 per cent expenditure will be incurred on capital enhancement.																								We are also promoting the wireless segment with a focus on LAN products and wi-fi equipment sales, added Singh. The company is finalising arrangements with two major airports to set up wi-fi hubs. The demand for wireless products has been growing at a healthy rate in India and product prices are expected to come down by one-third in the next two years.
